r\n<p>\r\n\tIt&rsquo;s worth noting that although the districts only represent about 5 percent of all school districts in New Jersey, they educated nearly 20 percent, or one-fifth, of students during the 2010-11 school year.<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\t<strong>Our ruling</strong><br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tAt the University of Notre Dame, Christie claimed &quot;we give 31 (former Abbott) districts 70 percent of the aid.&quot;<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tThe governor wasn&rsquo;t too far off. Between K-12 aid and preschool aid, the former Abbott districts are slated to receive about 60 percent of the state dollars allocated in the 2011-12 school year. We rate the statement Mostly True.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n\tTo comment on this ruling, go to <a href=\"http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/12/politifact_nj_chris_christie_c.html\">NJ.com</a>.</p>\r\n", "ruling_comments_date": "2011-11-30T17:27:05.830214", "ruling_date": "2011-12-01T07:30:00", "ruling_headline": "Chris Christie claims 31 former Abbott districts receive 70 percent of the state aid", "ruling_headline_slug": "Chris-Christie-claims-31-former-Abbott-districts-r", "ruling_link_text": "Gov\u2019s on the money", "ruling_state": null, "source_documents": null, "sources": "<p>\r\n\t<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OfTw1gsMtyw\" id=\"internal-source-marker_0.36660608824136165\">Gov. Chris Christie speech at Notre Dame Forum</a>, Nov. 18, 2011<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tNew Jersey Department of Education, <a href=\"http://www.state.nj.us/education/archive/abbotts/\">DOE Archives: Abbott History</a>, accessed Nov. 25, 2011<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tEducation Law Center, <a href=\"http://www.edlawcenter.org/cases/abbott-v-burke.html\">Abbott v. Burke Overview</a>, accessed Nov. 25, 2011<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tNew Jersey Supreme Court, <a href=\"http://lawlibrary.rutgers.edu/courts/supreme/m-1293-09_5.opn.html\">Abbott v. Burke Decision</a>, May 24, 2011<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\tNew Jersey Department of Education, <a href=\"http://www.state